"abstract": "Let me in! Let me in!" shouted the angry troll, sparks flying from his fury. "Wait," said the cat sweetly, "I will tell you how the rye became this cake!"
}

{
"abstract": "Get out of the way and let me in!" cried the troll in rage. The cat pretended not to hear him and talked continuously, blocking his entry with the cake whenever he tried to enter. After speaking at length, the cat exclaimed, "Look at the shining maiden coming behind the mountain!" When Helge-Hal in the Blue Hill turned his three heads to look, the sun rose, turning him to stone. Ebe then inherited all the troll's possessions: livestock, a golden castle, and bags of money."
}

{"abstract": ""Alas, alas!" cried the bull in distress. "What have you done! Now I must fight for my life. But keep the leaf carefully!" When they reached the forest's end, a three-headed troll rushed up, demanding "Who has touched my forest?" The bull claimed equal rights, declaring "The forest is as much mine as yours!" They engaged in fierce combat, with the bull goring and butting with all his might. Though equally strong, the troll eventually fell after a day's battle, leaving the bull severely wounded and barely able to walk. They rested while the queen's daughter used the healing ointment from the troll's girdle to restore the bull's strength.

After many days of wandering, they entered a magnificent silver forest, where every tree, branch, leaf, and bud was pure silver. Another troll appeared, leading to the same confrontation over forest ownership. This battle lasted three full days before the bull emerged victorious, though he was left weak and bleeding profusely. Again, the king's daughter applied the troll's healing ointment, and they remained there until he recovered.

Their final and most terrifying encounter was with a nine-headed troll, whose appearance was so frightful that the king's daughter could barely look at him. The ensuing battle was the most fearsome yet, as the bull's task was complicated by the troll's heads breathing life back into each other whenever one was destroyed. After a week of brutal fighting, the bull finally prevailed but was left in such a wretched state that he couldn't even move or speak. The king's daughter, acting on her own initiative, took the healing ointment from the troll's girdle and treated his wounds. The severity of this final battle required them to rest for three whole weeks before they could continue their journey."}
